item.title: Holy Hand Grenade of Antioch
item.description: This is a remix of Gsohm's Holy Hand Grenade. It has 5 changes... A hole in the crest to accommodate the cross. A hole in the top to do same. An extension of the cross to act as pin on the grenade. And two strips of PLA across the bottom and top to extend and trap the 3D raft so that supports to the middle won't come loose during the print, these strips are only 1x0.5 mm wide so as to be removed after the build. Remodelled with Openscad. Imported STL and added (or subtracted) as needed.

item.title: Mario Automaton
item.description: My partner and I were assigned the job of creating an automaton for this project. Automatons are basic systems that use cams and followers to perform a repeating motion or function. My partner and I came up with the idea of creating a "Super Mario video game scene" in which various characters from the game do simple actions to bring the setting to reality.  The hypnotic motions of the cams that lift and descend the followers are all controlled by a simple lever twist! This 23.5cm X 7.5cm X 16.5cm piece turned out great! This is also a very fun project if you are a fan of Mario!

item.title: [FD3S RX7] Cowl Screw Cover Kit
item.description:
Who isn't missing a cowl screw cover at this point? After years of sitting exposed to the elements the OEM plastic cowl screw covers weaken to the point of being extremely brittle causing them to just disintegrate by looking at them.

Sadly there is no way to buy OEM replacement screw covers, at least there wasn't until now! We're happy to offer a full direct replacement kit for the cowl screw covers. The kit includes 2 large oval screw covers and 6 small circle covers.

item.title: Ikea Hinge base
item.description:
The original Ikea element is casted in "Zamac" (light metallic material Al-Zn). Although it is a metallic element, it regularily fails and always at the same location. However, it is commonly known, that the manufacturing process imight create schrinkages at the very location of reduced sections. On top of this, this element is casted (for obvious economic reasons) and the void under the pressure zone adds fragility to it. One of the solution is to copycat the existing element AND to add a supporting section under the pressure screw. If rigidity is not sufficient, another option is to use a metallic insert right under that position too.
The proposed design is the simplest and seems working since weeks now.

item.title: Helicopter Automaton
item.description:
The purpose of this experiment was to create a functioning automaton, defined as a relatively self-operating machine. My partner Shreesh and I were inspired to construct a helicopter automaton. In our design, the helicopter launches up and down and has spinning blades attached. If you have never made an automaton before, this is the project to try out! While our design appears complex and challenging, Solidworks allows for a smooth design process and is the perfect platform for beginners.

In order to create vertical movement, a semi-circular attachment piece was inserted through the left hole at the bottom of the helicopter and capped off with an end piece. Then, this piece was placed atop an eccentric cam (attached to the handle), inside the base of the automaton. To create the spinning mechanism, another semicircular attachment piece was inserted through the helicopter, this time on the right side and with a loose fit, to ensure mobility. At the top of this piece, the blades were twisted on, while at the bottom a regular cam capped off the end. This cam was then placed at a slight angle on top of another eccentric cam. When the handle, equipped with both eccentric cams turned, the helicopter was able to move up and down steadily and the blades were able to spin. The rough dimensions of this project are 20 cm x 8 cm x 16 cm.

Design Inspiration: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yYcm3Ml2vr8
item.author: nwilson2022

item.title: Cafflano Kompresso Dosing Funnel, Tamper and Tamping Base
item.description:
This is a set of tools for Cafflano Kompresso manual espresso coffee brewing tool.

  • 47mm Funnel for dosing
  • 56.5mm Tamper
  • Tamping base

Dosing:
Using the 47mm funnel designed for the filter basket of the Cafflano Kompresso will make it easy to dose ground coffee into the basket and also prevents coffee going outside the basket.

Tamping:
The 47mm tamper should fit to the filter basket. Not too tight, not too lose.
When tamping, if you place the filter basket on a flat surface for tamping, there will be a gap between the metal filter and the surface. So if you press the tamper too hard, the metal filter may be bent. To prevent that, I designed a tamping base that supports the metal filter from the back and that will allow you to press harder and also make the coffee flat.

All the parts can be printed as is without any support, but I highly recommend printing with brim to keep the object attached on the print bed.
